{{Greek Alphabet|letter=alpha}}
'''Alpha''' (uppercase {{Script|Grek|'''Α'''}}, lowercase {{Script|Grek|'''α'''}}; {{lang-grc|ἄλφα}}, ''álpha'', <small>modern pronunciation</small> ''álfa'') is the first [[Letter (alphabet)|letter]] of the [[Greek alphabet]]. In the system of [[Greek numerals]], it has a value of 1.

It was derived from the [[Phoenician alphabet|Phoenician]] and [[Hebrew]] letter [[Aleph (letter)|aleph]] [[Image:phoenician aleph.svg|20px|Aleph]] - an [[ox]] or [[leader]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iwWuY9tAVq8C Chambers concise dictionary] p.30 Allied Publishers, 2004 {{ISBN|9798186062363}} Retrieved 2017-02-06</ref>

Letters that arose from alpha include the [[Latin]] [[A]] and the [[Cyrillic]] letter [[A (Cyrillic)|А]].

In English, the noun "alpha" is used as a synonym for "beginning", or "first" (in a series), reflecting its Greek roots.<ref>[http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/alpha Alpha - Definition and More from the Free Merriam-Webster Dictionary<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
